      <lg xml:id="TolE0170">
<l>aḷaviṟku niṟaiyiṟku moḻimuta lāki</l>
<l>yuḷaveṉap paṭṭa voṉpatiṟ ṟeḻuttē</l>
<l>yavaitāṅ</l>
<l>kacatapa veṉṟā namava veṉṟā</l>
<l>vakara vukaramō ṭavaiyeṉa moḻipa</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>There are only nine phonemes</l>
<l>which stand at the beginning of words</l>
<l>denoting measure and weight :</l>
<l>they are</l>
<l><foreign xml:lang="ta">k, c, t, p,</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="ta">n, m, v,</foreign></l>
<l>and also <foreign xml:lang="ta">a</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="ta">u</foreign> ;</l>
<l>so it is said.<note place="foot">Exx. :<foreign xml:lang="ta"> kalam, kaḻañcu, cāṭi, cīrakam, tūtai, toṭi,
          palam, pāṉai, nāḻi, nirai, maṇṭai, mā, vaṭṭil, varai, akal, antai, uḻakku.</foreign> It is interesting that obviously no item was available to Iḷampūranar with initial <foreign xml:lang="ta">u-</foreign> denoting weight. On the other hand, he quotes words denoting measurement and beginning with other phonemes, viz. <foreign xml:lang="ta">immi, ōraṭai, ōrātai.</foreign></note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
